The paper focuses on accelerating deep convolutional neural networks, which are commonly used in computer vision tasks (cs.CV). The proposed method involves identifying informative features for different instances, which is a form of feature selection and can be considered a machine learning technique (cs.LG). The paper also discusses the use of coefficient of variation as a measure for selecting appropriate layers, which is a statistical method commonly used in machine learning (cs.AI). Additionally, the paper involves the use of regularization to encourage sparsity in intermediate feature maps, which is a common technique in neural network optimization (cs.NE). Finally, the paper involves experiments conducted on benchmark datasets, which is a common practice in natural language processing and computer vision research (cs.CL).
